Gut microbial diversity during pregnancy and early infancy: an exploratory study in the Indian population

Shreyas V. Kumbhare, Dattatray S. Mongad, Dhrati V. Patangia

25/12/2019

Background

To study the gut microbiota during pregnancy and infancy, we analyzed gut microbial communities from 20 mother-infant dyads at different stages of pregnancy and early infancy. In total, we analyzed 80 fecal samples for profiling the gut microbial community using 16S rRNA gene-based sequencing. We observed no significant alterations in the gut bacterial diversity during pregnancy, however, significant alterations were observed during the period from birth to six months in infants, with a reduction in Staphylococcus and Enterococcus and an increase in Bifidobacterium and Streptococcus with a more stable anaerobic community at the age of six months.

Preprocessing

The raw reads (paired end reads) were analyzed using the dada2 pipeline (Callahan et al. 2016a). Denoising and pre-processing of the sequence reads were carried out using dada2 pipeline (Callahan et al. 2016a), while reference-based chimera removal was carried out using VSEARCH (Rognes et al. 2016). Taxonomy to the Amplicon Sequence Variants (ASVs) was assigned using SILVA database release 132 (Quast et al. 2013). Diversity analysis was carried out in R (R core team 2017) using phyloseq (Mcmurdie and Holmes 2013) and microbiome package (Lahti et al. 2017). The sparsity of the data was checked, and singletons were removed using the microbiome package (Lahti and Shetty et al., 2017). The phyloseq object was stored as phyloseq.rds and downstream analysis is describe in this document.

Compute prevalence and abundance of ASVs for infant samples

# Compute prevalence of each feature, store as data.frame
prevdf = apply(X = otu_table(ps.infant),
        MARGIN = ifelse(taxa_are_rows(ps.infant), yes = 1, no = 2),FUN = function(x){sum(x > 0)})
# Add taxonomy and total read counts to this data.frame
prevdf = data.frame(Prevalence = prevdf,
                      TotalAbundance = taxa_sums(ps.infant),
                      tax_table(ps.infant))
# plotting
ggplot(prevdf, aes(TotalAbundance, Prevalence / nsamples(ps.infant),color=Phylum)) +
  # Include a guess for parameter
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0.05, alpha = 0.5, linetype = 2) + geom_point(size = 2, alpha = 0.7) +
  scale_x_log10() +  xlab("Total Abundance") + ylab("Prevalence [Frac. Samples]") +
  facet_wrap(~Phylum) + theme(legend.position="none")

Ordination analysis

for infant samples

For ordination analysis rank tranformation was performed as described by Callahan et al. 2016

ps_ranks1 <- psinfant.final
abund1 <- otu_table(ps_ranks1)
abund_ranks1 <- t(apply(abund1, 1, rank))
write.table(abund_ranks1,file = "abund1_total.txt",sep = "\t")

abund_ranks1 <- abund_ranks1 - 375 # 90% of observed ASVs
abund_ranks1[abund_ranks1 < 1] <- 1
otu_table(ps_ranks1) <- otu_table(abund_ranks1, taxa_are_rows = F)
ps_ranks1
## phyloseq-class experiment-level object
## otu_table()   OTU Table:         [ 417 taxa and 40 samples ]
## sample_data() Sample Data:       [ 40 samples by 13 sample variables ]
## tax_table()   Taxonomy Table:    [ 417 taxa by 8 taxonomic ranks ]
# plotting ordination using Bray curtis distances
ps_ranks1_plot <- plot_ordination(ps_ranks1, ordinate(ps_ranks1, "MDS", "bray"), color = "Time.Point") + geom_point(size = 3)

ps_ranks1_plot + scale_color_manual(values=c("#58d68d",  "#D78D43")) + stat_ellipse(type = "t") + theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), panel.background = element_blank(), axis.line = element_line(colour = "black"))

Significance testing for ordination analysis using PERMANOVA

pairwise.adonis(phyloseq::distance(ps_ranks1, method = "bray"), sample_data(psinfant.final)$Time.Point, perm = 999, p.adjust.m = "fdr")

Beta dispersion analysis (inter individual variation)

psinfants_dist <- phyloseq::distance(ps_ranks1, method = "bray")
sampledf1 <- data.frame(sample_data(ps_ranks1))
beta1 <- betadisper(psinfants_dist, sampledf1$Time.Point, bias.adjust = TRUE)
permutest(beta1, pairwise = TRUE, p.adjust.methods= "fdr")

Differential abundance testing

To assess the differences between two groups, i.e., first trimester vs. the third trimester (mothers) and at birth vs. six months (infants), variance stabilization method was employed using the ‘DESeq2’ package (Love et al., 2014) as described previously (McMurdie and Holmes 2014) and differential abundance of the ASVs were calculated using the ‘DAtest’ package (Russel et al., 2018) and expressed in Log2fold change and significance testing was carried out using paired Wilcoxon rank sum test (to compare between time points) or Kruskal-Wallis test (for unpaired comparison) with BH based FDR correction.

for infant samples

ps_dds = phyloseq_to_deseq2(psinfant.final, ~SubjectID + Time.Point) # Paired design
gm_mean = function(x, na.rm = TRUE){
  exp(sum(log(x[x > 0]), na.rm = na.rm) / length(x))
}
geoMeans = apply(counts(ps_dds), 1, gm_mean)
ps_dds = estimateSizeFactors(ps_dds, geoMeans = geoMeans)
ps_dds = estimateDispersions(ps_dds)
abund = getVarianceStabilizedData(ps_dds) 
## You can use this transformed values to replace the values in the main phyloseq object for e.g. here replace values in psfinal.infant and then perform the wilcox sum rank test. Please make sure you create a new object and not replace the original phyloseq.
write.csv(abund, "vst_infant.csv")

for maternal samples

ps_dds2 = phyloseq_to_deseq2(psmother.final, ~SubjectID + Time.Point) # Paired design
gm_mean = function(x, na.rm = TRUE){
  exp(sum(log(x[x > 0]), na.rm = na.rm) / length(x))
}
geoMeans = apply(counts(ps_dds2), 1, gm_mean)
ps_dds2 = estimateSizeFactors(ps_dds2, geoMeans = geoMeans)
ps_dds2 = estimateDispersions(ps_dds2)
abund2 = getVarianceStabilizedData(ps_dds2) 
write.csv(abund2, "vst_mother.csv")

Testing prevalence and abundance of differentially abundant ASVs

# creating sequence table of differentially abundant ASVs for meconium and six month samples
seqtab.infant.diff.asv.6m <- t(as.data.frame(otu_table(pssix.rel)))[as.character(wilcox.out.infant$Feature),]

# agglomeration at genus level
psmother_glom <- tax_glom(psmother.final, "Genus", NArm = TRUE)
psmother_glom

# VST transformation of the agglomerated phyloseq object
mother.glom.vst = phyloseq_to_deseq2(psmother_glom, ~SubjectID + Time.Point) # Paired design
gm_mean = function(x, na.rm = TRUE){
  exp(sum(log(x[x > 0]), na.rm = na.rm) / length(x))
}
geoMeans = apply(counts(mother.glom.vst), 1, gm_mean)
mother.glom.vst = estimateSizeFactors(mother.glom.vst, geoMeans = geoMeans)
mother.glom.vst = estimateDispersions(mother.glom.vst)

# replacing vst transformed counts in phyloseq object

Influence of feeding pattern was not tested at six months as all of the infants were partially breast fed(none of them were exclusively breast fed). The only factor that could explain variation in the maternal sample was the dietary pattern during pregnancy. So we decided to determine the significant taxa between the two groups categorized by diet in the maternal samples.

# VST transformation was carried out using unpaired design, as the differences were seen independent of time point.
mother.diet.vst = phyloseq_to_deseq2(psmother.final, ~Diet) # Unpaired design
gm_mean = function(x, na.rm = TRUE){
  exp(sum(log(x[x > 0]), na.rm = na.rm) / length(x))
}
geoMeans = apply(counts(mother.diet.vst), 1, gm_mean)
mother.diet.vst = estimateSizeFactors(mother.diet.vst, geoMeans = geoMeans)
mother.diet.vst = estimateDispersions(mother.diet.vst)
abund.mother.diet = getVarianceStabilizedData(mother.diet.vst)

# replacing vst transformed count in phyloseq object
psmother.diet.vst <- psmother.final
otu_table(psmother.diet.vst) <- otu_table(abund.mother.diet, taxa_are_rows = TRUE)
psmother.diet.vst
## phyloseq-class experiment-level object
## otu_table()   OTU Table:         [ 538 taxa and 40 samples ]
## sample_data() Sample Data:       [ 40 samples by 13 sample variables ]
## tax_table()   Taxonomy Table:    [ 538 taxa by 8 taxonomic ranks ]
# differential abundance testing
mother.diet.test <- DA.kru(psmother.diet.vst, predictor = "Diet", relative = FALSE, p.adj = "fdr")
write.csv(mother.diet.test, "mothers_diffAbund_asv_diet.csv", row.names = TRUE)
